'''Kose no Kamusaki no Osamu''' (巨勢神前 訳語, dates of birth and death unknown) was a [[nobility|nobleman]] and military figure of the [[Asuka period]]. His {{ill|Kabane|ja|カバネ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabane|qq=}} title was {{ill|Omi|ja|臣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Omi|qq=}}.
== Lineage == The Kose no Kamusaki clan (巨勢神前臣) was a branch of the {{ill|Kose clan|ja|巨勢氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kose clan|qq=}} that resided in {{ill|Kanzaki District, Shiga|ja|神崎郡 (滋賀県)|lt=Kanzaki District|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanzaki District, Shiga|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi Province|qq=}}. In the 4th year of Emperor Tenji's reign (665), it was recorded that: {{quotation|Again, over 400 men and women of Baekje were relocated to Kamizaki District in Ōmi Province.<ref name="#1">''Nihon Shoki,'' Emperor Tenji, 4th Year, 2nd Month entry.</ref>}} This area became a refuge for Baekje nobles like {{ill|Kishitsu no Jushi|ja|鬼室集斯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishitsu no Jushi|qq=}}, who fled to Japan after Baekje’s fall. Another record states: {{quotation|In the same month (March), rice fields were granted to the people of Baekje in Kamizaki District.<ref name="#1"/>}}
== Career == In the 2nd year of Emperor Tenji’s reign (663), Osamu led troops as a middle general during the campaign against {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Silla|qq=}}, serving under the senior general {{ill|Kamitsukeno no Wani no Wakako|ja|上毛野稚子|1=Kamitsukeno no Wakatoko|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsukeno no Wani no Wakako|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsukeno no Wakatoko|qq=}} and rear general {{ill|Abe no Hirafu|ja|阿倍比羅夫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe no Hirafu|qq=}}. He reportedly commanded an army of 27,000 soldiers.<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' Emperor Tenji, 2nd Year, 3rd Month entry.</ref> His involvement in the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Baekgang|qq=}} is mentioned,<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' Emperor Tenji, 2nd Year, 8th Month, 27th and 28th Day entries.</ref> but whether he survived and returned to Japan remains unclear.<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' Emperor Tenji, 2nd Year, 9th Month entries (7th, 11th, 13th, 24th, and 25th Days).</ref>
